That’s a perfect next step. You can add a **print stylesheet** so the page doubles as a clean download or PDF without changing your main layout.

Here’s the basic approach:

```css
@media print {
  /* Set all backgrounds to white for readability */
  body {
    background: #fff;
    color: #000;
  }

  /* Remove navigation and skip link so only content prints */
  nav.top-nav,
  .skip-link {
    display: none;
  }

  /* Add a clear hierarchy for print readers */
  h2 {
    page-break-before: always; /* start each section on a new page */
    color: #000;
  }

  /* Inputs and textareas appear as blank lines for handwriting */
  input[type="text"],
  textarea {
    border: 1px solid #000;
    background: none;
  }

  /* Optional: make footer always appear at the end of the last page */
  footer.page-footer {
    page-break-after: avoid;
    border-top: 1px solid #000;
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }
}
```

**How it behaves**

- When someone selects “Print” or “Save as PDF,” the calming blue/green backgrounds are stripped away, leaving crisp black‑and‑white text.  
- Each major section starts on a new page so exercises have space.  
- The navigation disappears, giving a tidy, workbook‑like result.  
- Users can either write responses by hand if they print or type them before exporting to PDF.

You can test this quickly by loading your page in the browser, using **File → Print → Save as PDF**, and checking that spacing and page breaks feel balanced.

